election_record.label: Massachusetts 1802 Lieutenant Governor

overview.note: Caleb Strong and Elbridge Gerry were candidates for Governor.

"The joint committee raised to examine the returns of votes for GOVERNOR and LIEUTENANT-GOVERNOR reported, that the whole number of votes for Governor, was 49,583;--of which HIS EXCELLENCY CALEB STRONG, Esquire, Had 29,983, and he was declared elected. The votes for LIEUTENANT-GOVERNOR, were 46,386--of which HIS HONOR EDWARD H. ROBBINS, Esq. Had 28,371, and was declared elected. The votes for General Heath, for Lieut. Governor, (and scattering votes0 were 18,069; making a majority for Mr. ROBBINS of 10,248. We give these particulars, for the information of the Editors of the Aurora and National Intelligencer:--who have been laboring hard to convince the southern Virginians, that the votes given for Governor STRONG were no evidence of the true politics of Massachusetts; for that many good democrats alias northern Virginians, had in the election preferred the amiable and moderate Gov. Strong to the petulent and recluse Mr. Gerry. But what will these ingenious gentelmen say, when they find that the majority for Lieutenant Governor Robbins over the democratic Gen. Heath, is as large in proportion as Governor Strong's over Mr. Gerry?--They surely will not say, that any true democrat would prefer Mr. Robbins to their General!" The Columbian Centinel. Massachusetts Federalist (Boston, MA). May 29, 1802.
